class Solution:
    def rotateString(self, s: str, goal: str) -> bool:
        if len(s) != len(goal):
            return False
        return goal in (s + s)

"""
Approach & Reasoning:
A string goal is a rotation of s if and only if:
- They have exactly the same length.
- goal appears as a contiguous substring of s + s.

This works because any cyclic shift of s (moving characters from front to back any number of times) will be a substring of length len(s) inside the doubled string s + s. Conversely, any substring of s + s of that length must be a rotation of s.

The check is performed in O(n) time (string search) where n = len(s), which is efficient given the constraints n <= 100.

If lengths differ, immediately return false (no rotation possible).
If s == goal (0 shifts), goal will appear at the start of s + s, so the condition holds.

Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(n) for the temporary doubled string
"""
